\section{Almost discrete spaces}\label{section_spaces}

A topological space is {\bf Boolean} if it defines a Boolean locale, that is, if its open subsets form a Boolean algebra.

Classically, a Boolean topological space which is also $T0$ (Kolmogorov) is necessarily discrete (see lemma \ref{prop. almost discrete} and proposition \ref{cor. almost discrete} below). So \emph{classically, a locale is discrete if and only if it is both Boolean and spatial} (recall that spatial locales correspond to spaces which are sober, hence $T0$). For this reason, Boolean locales/spaces are also called ``\emph{almost discrete}''. 

Of course, such a terminology is unjustified intuitionistically since non-trivial discrete locales/spaces are never Boolean. Actually, in view of proposition \ref{proposition overt Boolean}, no topological space with at least one point can be proved to be Boolean. So the problem arises of finding a definition of ``almost discrete'' which is well-behaved also intuitionistically.

Let ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$ be the interior operator on a space $X$. Given a set $D$ of points, there are at least two (classical equivalent) ways to define the topological closure of $D$. The usual one is to take $({\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}} D^c)^c$, where $(\ )^c$ is set-theoretic complement. The other possibility, which is the one commonly adopted in constructive approaches, is to consider the set ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} D$ of all adherent points of $D$; so $x\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} D$ if and only if $x\in A\Rightarrow D{\, \between \,} A$ for every open $A$. The latter definition results in an intuitionistically weaker notion of closure in the sense that ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} D{\subseteq } ({\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}} D^c)^c$ and hence  $D=({\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}} D^c)^c$ implies $D={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} D$ (every closed subset is weakly closed). Note that ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} D{\, \between \,} A$ $\Longrightarrow$ $D{\, \between \,} A$ for every subset $D$ and every open $A$.

We now look for some condition involving ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$ and ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$ which could be taken as the definition of ``almost discreteness''; of course, it should reduce to Booleanness under a classical reading.

Classically, the fact that $X$ is Boolean can be expressed by anyone of the following three conditions: (i) the pseudo-complement operator ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}(\_)^c$ on open sets is an involution, (ii) every open set is closed and (iii) every closed set is open. Accordingly, we consider three candidates for the definition of ``almost discreteness'', namely
(i) ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$, (ii) ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$ and (iii) ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$. In what follows, a space $X$ is said to be $T0$ if ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{y\}$ implies $x=y$ for every pair $x,y$ of points of $X$; also $X$ is $T1$ if ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}=\{x\}$ for every point $x$ in $X$.

\begin{lemma}\label{prop. almost discrete}
Let $X$ be a topological space with interior operator ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$ and weak closure operator ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$. Then:
\begin{enumerate}
\item if ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$, then ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$;
\item if ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}$ and $X$ is $T0$, then $X$ is $T1$;
\item if ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$ and $X$ is $T1$, then $X$ is discrete.
\end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
1. We must show that ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} A{\subseteq } A$ for every open set $A$. So let $x\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} A$. The set $B={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ is open by assumption and $x\in B$; therefore $B{\, \between \,} A$. This is ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}{\, \between \,} A$, which implies $\{x\}{\, \between \,} A$. So $x\in A$.

2. We first claim that $y\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ $\Longrightarrow$ $x\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{y\}$ for every $x,y\in X$. So let $y\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$. For every open $A$ such that $x\in A$, we have $y\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}{\subseteq }{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}} A=A$, that is, $\{y\}{\, \between \,} A$. This proves the claim. Therefore, from $y\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ we get both
${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{y\}{\subseteq }{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ and ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}{\subseteq }{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{y\}$; hence $y=x$ by $T0$. So $y\in{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ yields $y\in\{x\}$ for every $y$. This means that ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}\subseteq\{x\}$ for all $x$, that is, $X$ is $T1$.

3. For every $x\in X$ we have ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}\{x\}$ = ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ = ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}\{x\}$ = $\{x\}$. Therefore every subset of $X$ is open.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}\label{cor. almost discrete}
For a topological space $X$ the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $X$ is discrete;
\item $X$ is $T0$ and satisfies ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$.\footnote{If ${\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$ is replaced by $({\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}} (\_)^c)^c$, then the corresponding result no longer holds intuitionistically (because discrete spaces fails to be Boolean).}
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

In view of this result, we can define an {\bf almost discrete space} to be a topological space such that ${\mbox{\sf {\,int\,}}}{\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}={\mbox{\sf {\,cl\,}}}$ holds. 

